WEBVTT

00:10:59.729 --> 00:11:02.671
Whereas if you challenge somebody's
strongly held assumptions,

00:11:02.695 --> 00:11:04.767
they just say you're wrong
or you're stupid.

00:11:04.791 --> 00:11:06.174
MG: That's good, that's fun.

00:11:06.198 --> 00:11:08.135
AG: You've been working on the fit topic

00:11:08.159 --> 00:11:11.745
around questions of what does it take
to be effective or successful

00:11:11.769 --> 00:11:13.337
or a high-performer.

00:11:13.361 --> 00:11:17.085
And how much does my environment
and whether I fit it matter.

00:11:17.109 --> 00:11:18.712
And I'd love to talk about that.

00:11:18.736 --> 00:11:21.235
Can you tell us first
what you've been doing there?

00:11:21.259 --> 00:11:23.649
MG: Well, I wanted
to talk about basketball,

00:11:23.673 --> 00:11:28.949
because right now, the NBA
is this lovely little case study in fit.

00:11:29.406 --> 00:11:33.985
To backtrack, the kind of
intuitive position of basketball